    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-07-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-07-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="1548"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1548">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">123 Olive, William M.: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cabot</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-07-10">July 10,
                            1949.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received July 10—1:50 a. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2683. I issued the following statement to the press immediately following release
                    of Olive: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“I have instructed Mr. Olive, for his own protection, to make no public
                            statement regarding his case.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>After examining Olive, I issued the following statement to the press later in the
                    day: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“I have only the following to add to what I said this morning. I have
                            personally seen Mr. Olive’s injuries. We have had him examined medically
                            and have taken photographs. There is no doubt whatever that Mr. Olive
                            was brutally beaten by the police and that any statements such as that
                            which appeared in the <hi rend="italic">Liberation Daily</hi> this
                            morning were obtained as a result of the barbarous treatment he
                            received. On the other hand, I am gratified and reassured to find that
                            the higher authorities, once the matter was brought to their attention,
                            arranged for his speedy release.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Repeated Canton 867; Nanking 1502.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cabot</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
